body: "Implement the storage/runtime foundation for first-class plans.\n\nScope:\n- Add built-in item type `Plan` while allowing agents to type `--type plan` through the existing case-insensitive resolver.\n- Store Plan items in `.agents/pm/plans/` using the same TOON/front-matter/history mechanics as Epic, Feature, Task, etc.\n- Add strongly typed plan metadata fields or equivalent normalized metadata support: `plan_mode`, `plan_scope`, `plan_harness`, `plan_steps`, `plan_decisions`, `plan_discoveries`, `plan_validation`, and `plan_resume_context`.\n- Ensure Plan items participate in context/list/search/stats/validate/history like all other types.\n- Search indexing must include plan scope, step text, decisions, discoveries, validation, dependencies, linked files/docs/tests, comments, notes, and learnings.\n\nResearch constraints from parent:\n- Codex-style plans must be living, self-contained, validated, and resumable by a future stateless agent.\n- Claude/Cursor-style plan modes require read-only planning before approval, reviewable steps, and progress/status updates.\n- Reuse normal pm item history rather than inventing a sidecar plan artifact.\n\nImplementation hints:\n- Start at `src/types.ts` and `src/core/shared/constants.ts` for built-ins and folders.\n- Confirm `src/core/item/type-registry.ts` continues resolving lowercase `plan` to `Plan`.\n- Update settings/default folder initialization and any tests that assert exact built-in type lists or folder maps.\n- Update help/contracts/completion/runtime schema expectations to include Plan.\n\nAcceptance:\n- `pm create --type Plan ...` and `pm create --type plan ...` both create Plan items.\n- Plan items are written under the normal item store and have history streams.\n- `pm contracts --command create --flags-only --json` includes Plan in runtime schema types.\n- `pm search` can find Plan items by plan scope, step content, decisions, and linked item context.\n- Focused tests cover built-in constants, type registry resolution, create/update behavior, search corpus, stats/context/list behavior, and history preservation."
